{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518004"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:59:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:59:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12855"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12855"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.13,0.08,0.06,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5298"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97445"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5298"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12855"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80055"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1887"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9021"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33387"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97445"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-month history of fatigue, weakness and shortness of breath which has been slowly worsening. Over the last few days she has noticed numbness and tingling sensation in her hands and toes and some mild difficulty in swallowing food. She has a history of Hashimoto thyroiditis and takes levothyroxine. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale. Her pulse rate is 115/min and blood pressure 107/70 mmHg. Her tongue appears smooth and red. The remainder of the examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 80 g/L (120-150)\u003Cbr /\u003EMean corpuscular volume: 110 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings is most likely to be present on peripheral blood film examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyper-segmented neutrophils","Increased reticulocyte count","Heinz bodies","Reed-Sternberg cells","Burr cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features consistent with megaloblastic anaemia due to vitamin B12 deficiency, with both haematological and neurological manifestations. Her difficulty in swallowing could be explained by possible cranial nerve involvement from vitamin B12 deficiency, which can impair pharyngeal coordination. The vagus plays a key role in the initiation of swallowing. The atrophic glossitis (smooth, red tongue) may cause oral discomfort that can interfere with swallowing. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe association with Hashimoto thyroiditis suggests pernicious anaemia as the underlying cause. In megaloblastic anaemia, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyper-segmented neutrophils\u003C/strong\u003E (\u0026gt;5 nuclear lobes) are a characteristic finding on blood film due to impaired DNA synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased reticulocyte count\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate an appropriate bone marrow response to anaemia. However, in megaloblastic anaemia, DNA synthesis is impaired, leading to ineffective erythropoiesis and a low reticulocyte count despite severe anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeinz bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are denatured haemoglobin precipitates seen in oxidative haemolysis (e.g., G6PD deficiency) and are not associated with megaloblastic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReed-Sternberg cells\u003C/strong\u003E are diagnostic of Hodgkin lymphoma and would not be seen on a routine peripheral blood film. They are seen on lymph node or bone marrow biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBurr cells\u003C/strong\u003E (echinocytes) are typically seen in uraemia, liver disease, or post-splenectomy states, none of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of vitamin B12 deficiency would be confirmed by checking serum B12 levels, and if pernicious anaemia is suspected, testing for anti-intrinsic factor antibodies would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peripheral blood smear in megaloblastic anaemia shows hypersegmented neutrophils (\u003E5 nuclear lobes).","The combination of macrocytic anaemia, neurological symptoms, and autoimmune disease suggests pernicious anaemia.","Neurological manifestations of B12 deficiency include peripheral neuropathy and subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord."],"references":["Torrez M, Chabot-Richards D, Babu D, Lockhart E, Foucar K. How I investigate acquired megaloblastic anemia. International Journal of Laboratory Hematology. 2022;44(2):236\u201347.","Doust J. Diagnostic and management strategies for anaemia in adults. Aust Fam Physician. 2003;32(11):889-894."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80055"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12855"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80055"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-07T08:33:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-07T08:34:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5298"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97445"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"sel